"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多电视评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wild-sides-review-survival-of-the-fiercest-a683a104?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《The Wild Sides》评论：最激烈的生存</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 3 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/poisoned-the-dirty-truth-about-your-food-review-netflix-farm-to-table-to-hospital-9444a103?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《中毒：关于食物的肮脏真相》评论：从农场到餐桌再到医院</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 1 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-big-nailed-it-baking-challenge-review-netflix-nicole-byer-376b7e62?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“大佬‘成功了！’”烘焙挑战赛回顾：蛋糕与混乱</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 1 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/r-m-n-review-hatred-poisons-the-mind-1768fe3c?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《RMN》评论：仇恨毒害心灵</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 27 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>对于观众来说，了解《爱丽丝·哈特的失落之花》中家庭暴力的角度可能是有好处的。虽然大多数暴力事件都被相当谨慎地处理，或者完全在银幕外处理，但它是故事的一个主要部分，既令人不安又独特：琼，因为她必须如此而坚强，为受虐待的妇女经营一个避难所，它的表面是一个巨大的本土花卉农场，名叫桑菲尔德（Thornfield）。尽管她是一家批发花店，而且鲜花的“语言”是一个贯穿始终的主题，但占地多英亩的桑菲尔德的真正目的却保密，以至于引起了镇民的怀疑。其中包括当地的图书管理员莎莉（阿舍·凯迪饰），她报告了爱丽丝明显的虐待行为，在这个女孩因悲剧而变得沉默后，她将琼的收养视为自己的狄更斯式噩梦，从而危及桑菲尔德的安全。莎莉有自己的秘密，她对整个故事一无所知。在很长一段时间内，观众也没有这样做。</p><p>坐在座位边上和只是坐在那里挠头是有区别的。琼是一个强有力的角色，她外出时会被那些滥用她的“花”的人故意殴打——将暴力男子引诱至他们的短绳末端——以便将他们送回监狱。她带着一支随时可以使用的步枪在桑菲尔德巡逻。她并不是胆怯的紫罗兰。但她也不是澳大利亚山谷里的百合花。正如盛开的爱丽丝（阿丽西娅·黛布南-凯莉饰）将会发现的那样，桑菲尔德发生的不仅仅是植物学，报应的种子正在风中盘旋，并在风下飘荡。不过，她可能不想等到收获季节。我们也不能。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。安德森是《华尔街日报》的电视评论家。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 21:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lost-flowers-of-alice-hart-review-thorny-drama-on-the-australian-prairie-781af5e8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lost-flowers-of-alice-hart-review-thorny-drama-on-the-australian-prairie-781af5e8<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电视/广播</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Wild Sides’ Review: Survival of the Fiercest]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> BBC America 的三集系列节目在 AMC+ 上播出，讲述了大象、猎豹和狒狒等五个动物家族在干旱的博茨瓦纳寻找水源的危险而血腥的旅程。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590124522388167114"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829335?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">泥泞的小象</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Wim Vorster/BBCA </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590124522388167114"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">约翰·安德森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 5:28 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wild-sides-review-survival-of-the-fiercest-a683a104"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>很难想象，温柔会阻止《狂野的一面》给我们带来大多数自然项目的回报——一个物种被另一个物种实际追逐和捕获。这部以博茨瓦纳为背景的连续剧中有足够多的随机内脏，足以容纳昆汀·塔伦蒂诺制作的《理发师陶德》，所以不可能是精致的东西让镜头被切掉。也许他们只是错过了镜头？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p><strong>狂野的一面</strong></p><p><em>周六晚上 8 点开始，BBC America；流媒体 AMC+</em></p></div></div><p>这似乎也不太可能，因为 BBC America 的这段演示中包含了大量亲密、详细的照片，其主要内容是五个动物家族——大象、猎豹、豹子、豺狼和狒狒——到一条已经被破坏的河流的旅程。减少为细流。这部由三部分组成的剧集以博茨瓦纳东部的马沙图禁猎区为背景，据解说员科林·萨蒙（《东区人》、《生化危机》）介绍，已经四年没有下过“正常”的雨了。在你的口干舌燥之前，请放心，到了第二集，将会有一场圣经般的倾盆大雨，以及对那些生活在博茨瓦纳、南非和津巴布韦交汇处的人们来说，一系列全新的问题。</p><p>正如非洲自然项目中的情况一样，某些物种、它们的捕食者、竞争对手和那些保持环境整洁的食腐动物之间存在着一场生存之战。有时也有合作——大象知道如何找到宝贵的水并分享它——以及不可避免的拟人化：鲑鱼先生将人类的品质赋予某些动物，就像我们都倾向于做的那样，偶尔充当拉拉队队长对于某些动物而不是其他动物；鬣狗在静止不动时似乎躲藏起来，从来没有得到任何叙述者的喜爱，它们是大自然的恶棍之一。另一方面，豹子的代表在绝望时期“沦落”为食腐动物（“多么尴尬，”萨尔蒙先生说），但它仍然是猫科动物和一般生物中最美丽的。猎豹紧随其后。大象虽然笨拙，但却高贵。关于狒狒，说得越少越好。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多电视评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lost-flowers-of-alice-hart-review-thorny-drama-on-the-australian-prairie-781af5e8?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《爱丽丝·哈特的失落之花》评论：澳大利亚大草原上的棘手戏剧</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 3 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/poisoned-the-dirty-truth-about-your-food-review-netflix-farm-to-table-to-hospital-9444a103?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《中毒：关于食物的肮脏真相》评论：从农场到餐桌再到医院</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 1 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-big-nailed-it-baking-challenge-review-netflix-nicole-byer-376b7e62?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“大佬‘成功了！’”烘焙挑战赛回顾：蛋糕与混乱</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 1 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/r-m-n-review-hatred-poisons-the-mind-1768fe3c?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">《RMN》评论：仇恨毒害心灵</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 27 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>《狂野一面》中的豺狼夫妇被称为莫洛夫妇，他们有一窝幼崽，并花费大量时间保护幼崽免受搭档的伤害。莫洛伊先生和夫人。它们出没于猎豹莱克西，就像不肯离开的房客一样，不断地寻找残羹剩饭或直接偷食物。但它们更有趣，而不是可怕或恶毒。毕竟，它们不是鬣狗。</p><p> 《狂野的一面》令人兴奋，同时并没有提供太多我们以前从未见过的内容，尽管其中心思想——共同的跋涉和多个物种不可避免的交叉——是新颖的。干旱的程度也是如此——在下雨之前，人们想知道是否有人能挺过来，正如萨蒙先生所说，“就在你认为事情不会变得更糟的时候”，狮子出现了。随之而来的是残暴程度的螺旋式上升。狮子可能会得到很好的报道，但实际上它们很糟糕。</p><p>他们只得到了萨尔蒙先生的勉强赞赏，他以自己的方式作为叙述者，达到了介于查尔斯·丹斯的讽刺和大卫·阿滕伯勒的漫不经心的全知之间的程度。他确实比这两位先生有更多的机会来搞笑，或者至少是双关语：“美好的一天的开始，”他注意到两只年轻的猎豹正在吃，是的，一只黑斑羚的头。在一个节目中，这是一个令人惊讶的奇思妙想，在这个节目中，生活可能是肮脏的、残酷的、短暂的和不可预测的，但往往是美丽的，尤其是对于我们这些不必生活的物种来说。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——约翰·安德森是《华尔街日报》的电视评论家。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 21:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wild-sides-review-survival-of-the-fiercest-a683a104</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wild-sides-review-survival-of-the-fiercest-a683a104<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电视/广播</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Real Reason You’re Having a Hard Time Getting Things Done at the Office]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在家工作改变了我们的大脑。我们需要更多的办公时间来解决这些问题。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828457/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图：Sam Kelly/《华尔街日报》，iStock (11)<span>照片插图：Sam Kelly/《华尔街日报》，iStock (11)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ray-a-smith" itemprop="url" rel="author">雷·A·史密斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>如果你还没有恢复办公室的最佳状态，可能会有一个科学的解释。混合工作安排会扰乱我们的大脑。</p><p>沮丧的老板们在审视<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-return-to-office-rate-rises-above-50-for-first-time-since-pandemic-began-11675285071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">半空的办公室环境</a>后表示，2020 年之前在办公室全职工作的人不能像以前那样出现，这是没有道理的。但神经学家和行为科学家表示，对彼此有效合作的集体失忆症对他们来说是完全合理的。</p><p>一些员工已经失去了在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-open-office-is-out-seated-privacy-is-in-as-cubicles-make-a-comeback-11663189508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开放式办公室环境</a>中完成工作所需的肌肉记忆，就像松弛的二头肌一样，这种肌肉必须通过锻炼才能增强，教授兼神经病学系主任托马斯·卡迈克尔 (S. Thomas Carmichael) 说。加州大学洛杉矶分校大卫格芬医学院。</p><p>卡迈克尔说，经过多年的远程工作，我们大脑的选择性注意力技能和排除干扰的能力被削弱。那些喜欢在家工作的人可能不喜欢他的补救措施之一：让自己更频繁地在办公室工作。</p><p> “大脑真的很擅长理解突发事件，所以如果我们只是说‘我在家的时候就完成这件事’，我们也学不会它，”他说。</p><h3>淹没在“假设”的海洋中</h3><p>组织心理学家凯瑟琳·斯沃迪 (Cathleen Swody) 表示，在了解在家工作的有效性之后，人们心里产生了一种隐隐约约的不快感。许多员工在社交办公空间中失去了不受干扰的自主权。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828332?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">玛丽亚·巴比诺娃 (Maryia Babinova) 表示，即使是很小的办公室时间浪费也已成为一大烦恼。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛丽亚·巴比诺娃</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>早在 2021 年，纽约市的高级软件工程师玛丽亚·巴比诺娃 (Maryia Babinova) 曾尝试每周去办公室几天，但发现几乎不可能提高工作效率。</p><p> “我每天的前 30 到 45 分钟都用来和每个人打招呼，”她说。</p><p>巴比诺娃表示，即使是很小的办公室时间浪费也已成为一大烦恼。例如，当排队时，去办公室的咖啡机可能需要长达 15 分钟的时间。她说，在家里，咖啡因触手可及，让她能够专注于工作。</p><p>现在，只有当她的团队成员从另一个城市来访时，巴比诺娃才会亲自出现。在办公室，她处理的任务不需要太多的精神负担，因此她可以完成它们。</p><p>伦敦经济学院助理教授劳拉·M·乔治 (Laura M. Giurge) 教授工作时间科学课程，她表示，不断将 2023 年的办公室现实与其他远程工作设置进行比较可能会加剧员工的重新调整困境。</p><p>当人们开始思考如果环境不同的话生活会是什么样子时，他们很快就会陷入“假设”的海洋，这是一种被称为反事实思维的心理学概念。</p><p> “现在，当我们去办公室时，我们会看到家庭办公室的反事实情况，”朱尔格说。 “我们知道事情会好得多……我们可以完成更多的工作。”</p><p>我们很难忘记<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中午带着狗去散步</a>是多么美好，或者下午 4 点退出去开始吃晚饭并稍后重新登录是多么有帮助。心理学家表示，思考如何更好地利用时间会占用宝贵的脑力，分散我们对手头实际工作的注意力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>令人不安的安静</h3><p>习惯与背景噪音一起工作需要时间。</p><p>现在，许多工作场所变得更加安静，因为它们不再那么拥挤，这意味着，在一段死寂的时期，可能会被突然的噪音打断，这些噪音感觉被放大了，一整天都让人们一次又一次感到不安。即使是在一天在家孤独工作和第二天在嘈杂的办公室之间切换也会产生类似的效果。</p><p>康奈尔大学组织行为学教授凡妮莎·博恩斯 (Vanessa Bohns) 表示：“我们必须重新习惯所有这些干扰，才能做好工作。”她指出，研究表明，需要 20 分钟才能适应背景噪音，但在恢复噪音之前保持五分钟的安静会迫使大脑重新开始处理过程。</p><p>现在，许多员工和一些老板将办公室视为协作的场所，但并不是埋头进行个人工作的唯一场所。</p><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>去年发布的一项大规模调查中，84% 的员工表示，与同事交流是他们面对面工作的主要动机。超过 70% 的人表示，如果他们知道直接团队成员或工作朋友会在那里，他们会更频繁地去办公室。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否发现在办公室完成工作比大流行之前更困难？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “数据显示，我们不能只将办公室视为完成集中工作的地方，”微软未来工作部总经理科莱特·斯塔尔鲍默 (Colette Stallbaumer) 表示。</p><p> Lynn Dang 是达拉斯地区的一名软件开发人员，她利用三天的强制办公时间进行面对面的会议和不需要高度集中注意力的工作。</p><p>去年，当她回到办公室时，她发现自己无法像在家工作时那样专心阅读代码。大声的团队讨论以及在小隔间里无意中听到那些正在打电话或拨入视频会议的人的片面谈话，对她的感官造成了持续的攻击。</p><p> “这就像我必须在我的待办事项清单上找到一些能让我高效工作的事情，”她说。 “否则我将不得不继续加班或周末工作才能完成工作。”</p><p>写信给 Ray A. Smith： <a href="mailto:Ray.Smith@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ray.Smith@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1<author><![CDATA[Ray A. Smith]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> S·托马斯·卡迈克尔</category><category>凯瑟琳·斯沃迪</category><category>劳拉·M·乔治</category><category>凡妮莎·博恩斯</category><category>科莱特·斯托鲍默</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着地缘政治紧张局势加剧，前往世界第二大经济体的游客减少，东西方鸿沟扩大<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近日，上海机场人烟稀少，旅行社组织的境外旅游来华的人数大幅减少。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：劳尔·阿里亚诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">取消Covid-19限制</a>并重新开放边境半年后，几乎没有国际游客前来——这是中国与西方脱钩的另一个迹象，可能会产生长期负面影响。</p><p>外国游客的缺席在北京和上海等主要城市尤其明显，上半年到访这些城市的外国人人数总计不到 2019 年新冠疫情大流行前可比数字的四分之一。</p><p>在全国范围内，第一季度，只有 52,000 人次通过旅行社组织的旅行到达中国大陆，这是有全国数据的最新时期，而 2019 年第一季度有 370 万人次。与往年一样，近一半的游客来自自治岛屿台湾以及中国香港和澳门，而不是美国或欧洲等更远的地方。</p><p> “来自欧洲、美洲、日本和韩国的游客数量都在大幅下降，”半官方的中国旅游协会理事肖千惠在五月份的一次讲话中表示。</p><p>专家表示，海外游客和商人的减少意味着外国人亲眼看到中国并与当地人互动的机会减少，而这是缓解地缘政治紧张局势的一个重要因素。</p><p>游客稀缺也可能导致对华投资减少。研究公司荣鼎集团 (Rhodium Group) 的马克·维茨克 (Mark Witzke) 对政府数据进行的分析显示，第一季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">流入该国的外国直接投资降至</a>200 亿美元，而去年第一季度为 1000 亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019 年，新冠疫情爆发之前，南京的一座陵墓挤满了游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：苏洋/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>外国投资和入境人数下降之际，中国经济停滞不前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">房地产市场低迷</a>，青年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">失业率</a>创历史新高，人们越来越担心中国可能<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">陷入通货紧缩。</a>与今年前三个月相比，第二季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">中国经济几乎没有增长</a>。</p><p>抵达中国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">的航班数量不足</a>是造成抵达人数低的部分原因，航空公司尚未恢复到新冠疫情爆发前提供的服务水平。但中国和海外旅游专家表示，由于中国与西方关系恶化，外国游客也不愿前往，这让他们对访问更加谨慎。</p><p> 6月，美国政府发布旅行建议，警告美国人重新考虑前往中国大陆的旅行，因为所谓的“任意执行当地法律”，包括出境禁令和错误拘留的可能性。</p><p>波士顿商业顾问马特·凯利 (Matt Kelly) 表示，他对 15 年前骑自行车环游中国南方一座风景如画的山城桂林的旅行留下了美好的回忆。他又两次访问中国，但表示今天没有兴趣回去。</p><p> “我会回到我所熟悉的中国吗？是的！”他说。但现在，“中国似乎确实将自己描绘成非常反西方、反美国的人。这让我非常不安。”</p><p>位于宾夕法尼亚州的友好星球旅游公司（Friendly Planet Travel）是一家精品经营商，过去每年向中国派遣多达 1,500 名游客。其创始人兼总裁佩吉·戈德曼 (Peggy Goldman) 表示，自新冠疫情爆发以来，该公司还没有收到过任何要求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">马特·凯利，2008 年在中国桂林。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马特·凯利</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当她的团队研究人们在网上搜索的目的地时，“中国确实处于追踪的底部，”她说。 “围绕中国这个话题存在很多敌意。”</p><p>尽管高盛表示她相信中国最终会再次流行，但该公司尚未将其中国包裹重新上线。</p><p>总部位于奥斯汀的旅游科技公司 Mondee Holdings 的数据显示，2023 年上半年从北美到中国的休闲旅游约为 2019 年同期的 40%。 2019年，Mondee通过旅行社和其他中介机构销售了约50万个从北美飞往中国的航班，约占当年从北美飞往中国的所有航空旅行的五分之一。</p><p>哈里斯·布里肯律师事务所驻西雅图合伙人丹·哈里斯表示，尽管企业高管仍在询问前往中国的旅行，但许多人现在关注的是风险，而过去，他们想知道如何加快签证速度。为在中国的投资提供建议。</p><p> “公司非常非常关心他们的员工去中国。为什么他们不会呢？他提到了中国最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对西方尽职调查公司和其他公司进行调查</a>的消息，其中包括政府对贝恩公司等全球咨询公司进行突击搜查。“除非迫不得已，否则人们不会去中国。”</p><p>哈里斯过去经常去中国北京工作，并在青岛停留购买啤酒和海鲜，他表示，他已告诉一些高管，他们的风险很低。但近年来，在公开批评中国政府后，他本人不再前往。</p><p>中国文化和旅游部没有回应置评请求。</p><p>中国官员最近与美国、欧洲和日本的商业协会举行了会议<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，向他们保证</a>中国仍然欢迎外国投资。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2019年以来，张家界国家公园的游客量大幅下降。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：吴永兵/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>中国驻美国大使谢锋7月份在阿斯彭安全论坛上表示，两国游客应该互相访问。他建议举办旅游论坛并增加航班数量，并呼吁华盛顿调整其旅行建议。</p><p>外国游客的缺席不会像泰国或冰岛那样对中国造成伤害，因为这些国家的经济严重依赖游客。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">目前，中国游客在国内旅游上的支出比 2019 年更多</a>。</p><p>尽管如此，中国仍有许多企业依赖游客。缺乏它们意味着中国失去了向外国人展示更积极形象的机会。</p><p>中国中部的张家界国家公园是电影《阿凡达》中“浮山”的拍摄地，这里有令人惊叹的岩层，截至 5 月中旬，海外游客仅有 25,600 人次，而 2019 年前 5 个月的海外游客人数为 500,000 人次。</p><p>上海导游于雪（Snow Yu）过去带外国人参观的生意很红火，包括在 2017 年为金州勇士队和佐治亚理工学院黄夹克篮球队的高管担任导游。在疫情期间，边境基本关闭，他找了一份英语辅导的临时工作。</p><p>于已经回到了原来的工作岗位，主要带领当地的旅游团。但他们不需要他的英语能力，给的小费也较少。因此，他说他的收入比大流行前减少了近一半。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BD0F48A-0DA4-4CED-8A69-018103B38E36&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">拜登总统周日在日本七国集团会议结束的新闻发布会上表示，他认为美中关系可能出现解冻。照片：苏珊·沃尔什/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“世界需要互联，”他说，并补充说来自邻国的英语游客开始回来。</p><p>来自西方和东亚部分地区游客的下降已被俄罗斯游客数量的增加部分抵消，不过中国旅游专家表示，他们的消费有所减少。</p><p>今年6月，张家界国家公园邀请80多家国际旅行社进驻，其中大部分来自俄罗斯。当地官员承诺增加更多从中国北方邻国起飞的航班，或延长从中国其他城市起飞的现有航班。</p><p>旅游官员肖在讲话中呼吁中央政府提供更多支持。他强调，入境旅游可以“以类似于‘乒乓外交’的方式”帮助化解地缘政治紧张局势，他指的是20世纪70年代乒乓球运动员的交流，帮助中美关系解冻。</p><p>他引用了埃隆·马斯克母亲最近访问中国的例子，她在 Instagram 上发布了关于她的经历的积极信息。</p><p>另一个避开中国的群体是外籍人士，他们在前几年充当了中国社会与各自祖国之间的桥梁。许多人邀请家人和朋友来参观。</p><p> 37岁的投资顾问亚历山大·西拉科夫(Alexander Sirakov)去年8月从上海搬回祖国保加利亚。他说，他的外籍朋友圈子里的大多数人也都离开了，包括住在他大院里的 10 个外籍家庭中的 8 个。</p><p> “人们现在认为中国非常遥远，而且有些疏远，”他说。 “四年前正好相反，当时的中国非常开放、充满活力，是一个必去的地方。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——齐丽艳对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给范文欣： <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a​​83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Dallas Museum of Art Picks a Winner]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>博物馆选择马德里 Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos 公司对其 1984 年建成的 Edward Larrabee Barnes 大楼进行改造。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126142695494342"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828306?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos 获奖设计的鸟瞰图</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos/Malcolm Reading Consultants </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126142695494342"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">迈克尔·J·刘易斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 12:24 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-dallas-museum-of-art-picks-a-winner-9d3eedf0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><em>达拉斯</em></p><p>达拉斯艺术博物馆今天宣布，它选择了在美国鲜为人知的西班牙公司 Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos 来改造和扩建其拥有近 40 年历史的建筑。</p><p> DMA 是爱德华·拉拉比·巴恩斯 (Edward Larrabee Barnes) 1984 年的作品，这位建筑师以其庄严、礼貌的现代博物馆建筑而闻名。它已经相当陈旧了，不存在将其拆除或改造得面目全非的问题，就像他的后现代主义同时代人的博物馆所发生的那样。它的问题本质上更具逻辑性。</p><p>巴恩斯在一个被废弃的停车场和停车场边缘区域提供了一块大的矩形地块，将他的建筑转向内部。他的主轴线纵向穿过场地，形成了一条约 650 英尺长的内部街道。两边都是画廊，坐落在方形的亭子里，亭子之间有植物和铺好的人行道。他在北面、南面和东面设置了公共入口，并用连续的树木包围了整个建筑。这个想法似乎是为了让游客尽快进入博物馆，与外界隔绝。</p><p>这在当时是谨慎的做法，但现在不再是这样了。如今，DMA 是一个占地 60 英亩的热闹艺术区的中心，东边北哈伍德街有两座博物馆，北边有一个大型雕塑公园。因此，我们需要寻找一位能够“加强与社区的合作，建立更牢固的公民联系，通过新设施改变游客体验，并扩大教育和画廊空间”的建筑师。</p><p>建筑师通常是根据他们的资历和最近的工作来选择的，但选拔委员会的顾问建议邀请六名建筑师进行初步设计，并每人获得 5 万美元的津贴，另加费用。委员会联合主席詹妮弗·伊格尔（Jennifer Eagle）告诉我，“房间里有人倒吸了一口冷气。”但两位捐助者挺身而出，引发了近年来最不寻常的建筑竞赛。</p><p>从 154 家申请者中，最终选择了六家公司，每家公司都在博物馆设计或景观和基础设施方面拥有专业知识。通常建筑师之间的竞争是空虚的。在这种情况下，他们飞往达拉斯三天，这样他们就可以一起用餐和互动，然后在 5 月 13 日的公共论坛上展示他们的第一印象，建议他们如何接触该委员会。到了演讲当天早上，他们的精神都亢奋到了头晕目眩的地步。竞争对手之一利兹·迪勒 (Liz Diller) 开玩笑说，看到以前的同事为新公司工作，“就像看到以前的恋人与新的伴侣在一起一样”。</p><p> 7月10日，入围者的帅气模特亮相，让评选委员会松了一口气的是，“其中没有古根海姆！”但如果没有像弗兰克·盖里 (Frank Gehry) 的毕尔巴鄂古根海姆 (Guggenheim Bilbao) 那样充满疯狂创意的盛宴，竞争对手对巴恩斯 (Barnes) 作品的尊重程度差异很大。</p><p>处于这一范围的一端是极简主义者，例如大卫·奇普菲尔德（David Chipperfield），他通过使他提议的干预措施几乎看不见，除了一个由木材建造的谨慎的新画廊之外，表达了他对原始建筑的“深深的尊重”。另一端是 Diller Scofidio + Renfro，他们认为巴恩斯的城堡应该“不再冷漠”。它的提议是在博物馆的两端设置巨大的新入口馆，这种规模过大的附加设施使原来的建筑相形见绌。人们感觉，如果可以的话，它会冲走所有原来的建筑。</p><p>洛杉矶迈克尔·马尔赞建筑事务所的提议表面上更为激进，但在某种程度上尊重了巴恩斯内部街道原始设计的精髓。马尔赞先生想要拆除博物馆长长的北哈伍德街一侧的所有东西，将其内部街道开放给一条风景如画的“文化地毯”，这条地毯将一直延伸，形成从城市到花园再到博物馆的逐渐过渡。在这片绿色的地毯之上，隐现着一系列光滑的玻璃亭子，悬臂伸入太空，不接触地面。与其他设计的认真相反，这个设计呈现出顽皮的微笑。</p><p>正如布鲁克林植物园游客中心的设计师所期望的那样，韦斯/曼弗雷迪对景观给予了最大的重视。他们的灵感来自巴恩斯的景观设计师丹·凯利（Dan Kiley），他赋予了原始建筑沙漠中绿洲的特征。洛杉矶的约翰斯顿·马克利 (Johnston Marklee) 是另一家强调景观的公司，他们有一个富有灵感的建筑理念：采用巴恩斯大楼中唯一的曲线形式，即形成东入口的桶形拱形大厅，并在北侧和北侧的新扩建部分中重复这一形式。南。与 Diller Scofidio + Renfro 的提案不同，这里对原始精神进行了补充。</p><p>该委员会异常复杂，有五名受过专业训练的建筑师，其中包括博物馆馆长阿古斯丁·阿特亚加 (Agustín Arteaga)。最终，它选择了最微妙的项目，即 Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos 的项目，其方法是一丝不苟的显微手术，而不是粗暴的手势制作。阿特亚加先生告诉我，他们对公司“对巴恩斯遗产的尊重”感到震惊，尽管该公司正在“开放我们的堡垒”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828307?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nieto Sobejano 提议的广阔画廊景观</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Nieto Sobejano Arquitectos/Malcolm Reading Consultants</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>涅托·索贝哈诺提出的最明显的变化是在西北端新建一个大型画廊，以期待未来的礼物。这在巴恩斯模式中表现得尤为突出，即使在更大的规模上，也表现出同样精益的精确性和严谨性。但让这个决定变得对它有利的，也是阿特亚加先生最热情地谈到的，是他们改变了南入口的方式，让你穿过一个花园，“一个简单而美丽的姿态”，让你看到踏入博物馆之前的艺术；所有这些都体现了一种“诗歌”的精神，这个词不能轻易地应用于许多其他提交的内容。博物馆做出了正确的选择。</p><p>当然，这个初步概念在未来几年将会发生许多变化。会成功吗？时间会证明一切。但在一方面，达拉斯艺术博物馆已经取得了胜利，那就是它以新颖而巧妙的方式找到了自己的建筑师，世界可以从中学到很多东西。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。刘易斯在威廉姆斯教授建筑史，并为《华尔街日报》撰写建筑评论。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 04:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-dallas-museum-of-art-picks-a-winner-9d3eedf0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-dallas-museum-of-art-picks-a-winner-9d3eedf0<category>艺术评论</category><category>娱乐场所</category><category>博物馆/画廊/花园</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>建筑学</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>建筑学</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>娱乐场所</category><category>博物馆</category><category>画廊</category><category>花园</category><category>闲暇</category><category>款待</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workers to Employers: We’re Just Not That Into You]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在大流行后的经济中，我们生活得更多，工作更少<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102816"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="531" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827913?width=860&amp;height=531" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">大多数雇主已经不再敦促员工全职返回办公室。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安德鲁·卡瓦列罗-雷诺兹/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102816"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/greg-ip"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-733523/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">叶<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/greg-ip" itemprop="url" rel="author">格雷格</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>早期，远程工作看起来是双赢的：员工可以随时随地工作，而雇主则可以提高工作效率。</p><p>事实证明，这笔交易只实现了第一部分。员工仍然喜欢远程工作，但最近的研究发现，生产力并没有提高，而且完全远程工作的情况有所下降。</p><p>然而，大多数雇主已经放弃激励员工全职返回办公室。根据人力资源管理协会 (SHRM) 的数据，62% 的雇主至少在一段时间内提供远程工作的选择。人口普查局发现，39% 的员工在家远程办公，其中一半每周工作五天。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>这是自疫情爆发以来人们对工作态度发生更广泛转变的征兆。尽管劳动力市场历来紧张，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pay-raises-are-finally-beating-inflation-after-two-years-of-falling-behind-3e89bc2d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">直到最近工资的</a>增长速度还没有快于通货膨胀。原因之一是工人们不仅仅是为了钱讨价还价。他们还要求更多的非金钱补偿，例如带薪休假和灵活的工作时间。因此，他们投入的时间往往较少，或者在投入的时间内完成的工作较少。</p><p>这似乎让员工更加快乐。世界大型企业联合会 (Conference Board) 5 月报告称，2022 年<a href="https://www.conference-board.org/research/job-satisfaction" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">员工满意度较 2021 年大幅上升</a>，达到 1987 年调查开始以来的最高水平。这并不是因为员工发现自己的工作更有成就感，而是因为工作占用的生活时间更少。在调查的18个组成部分中，“工作兴趣”对今年满意度上升的贡献最小；工作与生活的平衡是最大的。 （工资接近中间水平。）</p><p> “按<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/labor-market-mystery-where-are-the-older-gen-z-workers-11668278379?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">你的工资工作</a>”、“ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/if-your-gen-z-co-workers-are-quiet-quitting-heres-what-that-means-11660260608?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">安静地辞职</a>”和“ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-career-goal-of-the-moment-is-a-lazy-girl-job-f5075c4e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">懒惰女孩的工作</a>”等模因证明，当今许多人对职业的重视程度较低。他们与首席执行官发生了冲突，这位首席执行官通常工作时间不合理，为了公司的利益而牺牲休闲和家庭时间，并认为其他人也应该这样做。结果是：试图强迫员工返回办公室的高管往往<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-ceo-says-employees-cant-work-remotely-after-all-and-they-revolt-81135399?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">会遭到反抗</a>。</p><p>传统观点认为，快乐的员工工作效率更高。这并不一定是因为快乐可以提高生产力，而是因为雇主为了留住最有生产力的员工，就必须让他们保持快乐——即使这意味着采取措施降低他们的生产力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=839822A9-3A5F-4A5D-9390-E94EDF4A2336&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fworkers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">人工智能在白领工作中发挥着越来越重要的作用，能够起草电子邮件、演示文稿、图像等。工人已经因技术而失业，一些首席执行官正在改变未来的招聘计划。 《华尔街日报》解释道。插图：雅各布·雷诺兹<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>工人们偏爱金钱以外的东西并没有什么不寻常的。加州大学圣地亚哥分校经济学家瓦莱丽·雷米在一封电子邮件中表示：“在上个世纪，平均工作变得更加愉快、不那么繁重。”原因之一是政府法规，“但部分原因是……工人的实际收入随着时间的推移而增加，他们决定将收入的一部分（通过接受较低的工资）‘花’在更好的工作设施上。”</p><p> Ramey 和 Neville Francis 在 2009 年的一项研究中报告称，25 岁​​至 54 岁的男性每周<a href="https://econweb.ucsd.edu/~vramey/research/Century_Published.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">平均工作时间</a>从 1920 年的 49.8 小时下降到 1940 年的 41.4 小时。这反映了从每周六天到五天的转变——正如众所周知的那样该法案由亨利·福特 (Henry Ford) 实施，后来写入 1938 年《公平劳动标准法》，该法案规定每周工作 40 小时以上的加班费必须支付加班费。</p><p>直到 1980 年，工作时间继续减少，尽管速度较慢。单独的数据显示，在过去的几十年里，美国的工作时间基本保持稳定，而欧洲的工作时间则呈下降趋势。</p><p>有迹象表明，疫情爆发后，美国人和欧洲人一样，更加重视工作与生活平衡中的“生活”部分，雇主也做出了回应。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="532" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827922?width=700&amp;height=532" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">员工喜欢在家工作，因为这样可以节省通勤时间和其他麻烦。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安德鲁·卡瓦列罗-雷诺兹/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>据SHRM称，提供带薪休假的雇主比例已从2019年的63%上升至目前的70%，提供带薪育儿假的雇主比例从28%上升至39%。根据人力资源顾问<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WTW" class="">WTW</a>的数据，父亲平均休假七周，母亲平均休假九周<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-workers-are-finally-taking-guilt-free-vacations-f5eb383f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">员工也享受更多假期</a>。自 2021 年以来，一些人享受了四十年来的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-to-sign-bill-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday-11623944038?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">第一个新联邦假期</a>，即六月节。</p><p>根据劳工部月度数据，结果是，尽管就业增长迅速，但员工现在的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lots-of-hiring-but-not-so-much-working-d4f01646?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">工作时间比 2019 年要少</a>。与此同时，其年度美国时间使用调查发现，在某一天实际工作的就业人数比例从 2019 年的 67.8% 下降到 2022 年的 66.1%，这是至少自 2003 年以来的最低水平。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827999?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>与此同时，工人投入的时间生产力却较低。商业部门的每小时产出在大流行初期猛增，然后在今年第一季度呈下降趋势，尽管在第二季度可能有所回升（劳工部周四报告最新数据）。</p><p>这些都是众所周知的不稳定数字。但其中一些可能反映了我们工作方式的变化。员工喜欢在家工作，因为这样可以节省通勤时间和其他麻烦，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">让他们可以在白天处理个人事务</a>，例如跑步或从日托中心接孩子。他们可以在晚上或周末补上错过的工作。</p><p>斯坦福大学的尼古拉斯·布鲁姆 (Nicholas Bloom) 和两位合著者进行的调查显示，员工认为在家工作的效率提高了 7.4%。他们的经理却持相反的看法，估计员工在家工作的效率会降低 3.5%。根据经济学家对最近研究的回顾，原因是在家与员工沟通更加麻烦和耗时，而社交互动和反馈的减少会削弱创造力和学习能力。</p><p> Many workers find distractions, from the fridge to the television, at home. The authors note international chess players perform worse remotely, despite the motivation of prize money and rankings, proof that “overcoming potential self-control issues may not be easy.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How has the power dynamic between employee and employer shifted in your workplace?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Employers might be less willing to let employees work from home if the economy eventually slides into a recession and unemployment rises. “We&#39;re probably not in steady state at this point, and some reversal of the movement toward remote work seems likely to me,” said Katharine Abraham, a labor economist at the University of Maryland.</p><p> Bloom is less sure.他和他的合著者得出的结论是，生产力的损失仅限于那些全职远程工作的人，而不仅仅是每周工作几天的人。即使生产力受到影响，成本节约也可能足以弥补。远程员工可能需要更少的办公空间、住在更便宜的地方并接受更低的工资：作者发现，员工认为每周在家工作两到三天相当于加薪 8%。 It will take more than the threat of unemployment to undo this shift in values.</p><p> Write to Greg Ip at <a href="mailto:greg.ip@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">greg.ip@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e<author><![CDATA[Greg Ip]]></author><category> Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Valerie Ramey</category><category> Katharine Abraham</category><category> Nicholas Bloom</category><category> economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Buying a Home From a Builder? What to Know First]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The do&#39;s and don&#39;ts of purchasing a brand-new home <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827447/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo illustration by Rachel Mendelson/The Wall Street Journal, Scott Olson/Getty Images <span>Photo illustration by Rachel Mendelson/The Wall Street Journal, Scott Olson/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101322"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001101322"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/veronica-dagher" itemprop="url" rel="author">Veronica Dagher</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-newly-built-home-tips-mistakes-437b3cbb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> For those frustrated with the lack of existing houses on the market, buying from a builder seems like a simple solution—until it isn&#39;t.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-home-sales-boom-builders-6c736630?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Brand-new homes</a> have become more popular in neighborhoods where homeowners are reluctant to put their homes on the market and forgo their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/low-mortgage-rates-home-sales-low-supply-899aab29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">low-interest-rate mortgages</a> .</p><p> New-home sales account for around 15% to 20% of all recent home sales and could reach 30% in some markets, compared with a historical average of 10%, said Lawrence Yun, chief economist at the National Association of Realtors.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The price gap between new homes and old ones has been shrinking and is the smallest in nearly 20 years, said Sheharyar Bokhari, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/RDFN" class="company-name">Redfin</a> senior economist.根据商务部的数据，2023 年 6 月售出的新房销售价格中位数为 415,400 美元。 That compares with $410,200 for existing homes, according to the NAR.</p><p> Builders, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pandemic-ignited-a-housing-boombut-its-different-from-the-last-one-11615824558?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fueled by pandemic profits</a> , are also offering incentives to help buyers reduce their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-20-2023/card/mortgage-rates-fall-by-most-since-march-hzzZcqsEcSvYn5evwFCi?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">mortgage rate</a> or closing costs.</p><p> Hayley and Tyler Dupee recently bought a brand new four-bedroom, two-bath home in Ladson, SC, for about $312,000, motivated by the builder-included incentives such as a smart-home security system and window blinds.</p><p> “It became a no-brainer to us that a new home was going to be the best option for us within our budget,” she said. The couple gave up on buying an existing home after seeing bidding wars and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/home-renovation-delays-plumbers-electricians-a9e3d8e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pricey renovations</a> needed.</p><p> Buyers might be able to move into an existing home more quickly but could face <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-homes-fixer-uppers-renovations-73e0202f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">expensive repairs and upgrades</a> .新房往往更贵，买家通常需要灵活调整入住日期，因为可能会延迟竣工。建筑商建造的房屋通常带有一些定制选项。 On average, it takes more than eight months to build a house, according to the Commerce Department.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What advice do you have for buying a newly built home?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> With a brand-new home, buyers might misunderstand their purchase contracts, cut corners in the wrong places and balk at delays, financial advisers and builders say.</p><p> Here are five things to consider when purchasing from a builder:</p><h3> 1. Which upgrades are worth it?</h3><p> Consider what upgrades are difficult and pricey to complete once the house is finished, be it a gas line for an outdoor grill or wiring for outlets. These improvements cost less when you are building the home, said Angie Hicks, chief customer officer at home-services company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ANGI" class="">Angi</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p> It is also important to think about your home&#39;s resale value when deciding where to spend or skimp, she said.</p><p> Invest in systems that keep your home running, such as plumbing and electrical, and in areas with a high return on investment, such as the kitchen, she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/1e355341-07d6-4ab3-a46c-131c535dad68.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> A simple way to save: Choosing a 36-inch upper kitchen cabinet instead of a 42-inch upper one might cost a buyer about $600 less, depending on size of kitchen, said</p> Donnie Evans, president of Altura Homes, a home builder in Dallas.<p></p><h3> 2. Choose which corners to cut</h3><p> There are some areas where buyers can reduce costs without compromising quality, said Evans.</p><p> Evans has shaved about $1,500 off the price of a roughly 2,000 square-foot home he built for customers by lowering the steepness of the roof from 8/12 pitch to 6/12. Angi 的希克斯表示，屋顶坡度将屋顶陡度表示为垂直高度与水平跨度的比率。 A roof that rises 6 inches in the span of 12 inches would have a 6/12 pitch.</p><p> Selecting square corners for the home&#39;s drywall instead of rounded ones could save about $200 in total for an average 2,000 square-foot house, said Evans. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/ab690f8e-c514-4e25-bbf5-cf14f2835360.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> 3. Read the fine print</h3><p> Home builders typically have some ability to substitute materials based on availability to meet deadlines.</p><p> Read the developer&#39;s contract carefully and note what choices can be overridden by the builder and in what circumstances, said Emily Irwin, senior director of advice at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WFC" class="">Wells Fargo</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> Irwin has clients who selected an interior paint color only to find out that the builder is exercising its right to use a different one.</p><p> Top-of-the line stoves and refrigerators, often displayed in model homes, aren&#39;t necessarily included in a standard builder home, said Jason Katz, a financial adviser with UBS Financial Services in New York City. Ask your builder what, if any, appliances are included with your house.</p><h3> 4. Have extra money ready</h3><p> Builders often have the right to increase prices based on material costs, said Charlene Wehring, a financial adviser in Bellville, Texas. If costs go up and buyers can no longer afford the home, they will probably lose their deposit after backing out of the deal, she said.</p><p> Read the contract carefully and factor this possibility into your budget.</p><p> Bokhari at Redfin advises setting aside roughly 10% to 15% for contingency budgeting, depending on the home&#39;s location, type and size. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7fd8f6f9-675e-48e3-8ba1-38e1040507ec.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> 5. Don&#39;t expect perfection</h3><p> Buyers sometimes think they don&#39;t need a home inspection before closing because their new home usually comes with a warranty, said Mark Barnes, a Realtor in Charleston, SC</p><p> A warranty often covers items such as materials, workmanship, system and structural defects.</p><p> Barnes recommends buyers get a pre-drywall inspection since a home&#39;s problems might not be discovered until after the warranty period ends.</p><p> Hicks at Angi said to get an inspection at three points during the home-building process: before the foundation is poured;在安装干墙之前，更容易解决电气问题； and at the end, to ensure everything is built to code.</p><p> Hicks recommends paying an independent inspector to check out the house.大多数买家花费 280 至 400 美元进行检查。 It is worth it, she said.</p><p> Some of the most common issues that inspectors find are humidity in the home, cracks in drywall or incorrectly installed siding.</p><p> Write to Veronica Dagher at <a href="mailto:Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Veronica.Dagher@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/71bc0361-db4b-4906-bd2f-516bd9b31bf4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-newly-built-home-tips-mistakes-437b3cbb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/buying-newly-built-home-tips-mistakes-437b3cbb<author><![CDATA[Veronica Dagher]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>Building Construction</category><category> Residential Building Construction</category><category>建造</category><category>Real Estate/Construction</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>Buying/Selling a Home</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Home Buying &amp; Selling</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>buying</category><category> selling a home</category><category> home buying &amp; selling</category><category> building construction</category><category> residential building construction</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[SALT Deduction Cap Vexes GOP After Vexing Democrats After Vexing GOP]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Tax bill stalls as Republicans in areas with high levies insist on changes <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105493"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828391?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Jason Smith is under pressure to raise or scrap the limit on the state and local tax deduction.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: J. Scott Applewhite/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105493"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/richard-rubin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Richard Rubin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 2 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/salt-deduction-cap-vexes-gop-after-vexing-democrats-after-vexing-gop-5da55434"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> WASHINGTON—The $10,000 cap on the state and local tax deduction is bedeviling Congress. Again.</p><p> Taxpayers who itemize deductions can get a federal break for state and local income- and property-tax payments. Republicans in 2017 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-gop-moves-toward-keeping-partial-state-and-local-tax-deduction-1507827859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">limited that deduction</a> to help pay for tax cuts, and the new restrictions largely pinched high-income people in high-tax states.</p><p> That decision split the GOP, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/democrats-salt-tax-cap-high-earners-11635460218?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">divided Democrats</a> who tried to repeal it, and just sparked yet another intraparty fight.</p><p> The latest dispute over what is colloquially known as the SALT cap pits a group of suburban Republicans against the rest of their party. The lawmakers, who largely hail from competitive districts in high-tax states, say they will block a GOP tax bill unless the top tax writer, Rep. Jason Smith (R., Mo.), agrees to raise or scrap the $10,000 limit.</p><p> “In my district, if you own a home and you have a job, you hit the $10,000 cap,” said Rep. Mike Garcia, a Republican who represents a Los Angeles-area district. “This issue and our ability to navigate the SALT is going to be what allows us to keep the majority.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828621?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Rep. Mike Garcia of California says GOP control of the House hinges on the state and local tax deduction cap.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·布兰登/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>In Congress, geography sometimes trumps ideology, and the SALT cap scrambles the usual partisan discourse regarding taxes. Republicans oppose raising taxes on top earners, but most support the cap because it reduces what they see as a federal subsidy for residents of high-tax states. Democrats who oppose the cap run into objections in their own party because the break mainly benefits high-income people.</p><p> The SALT cap, meanwhile, is most hated in suburban districts in high-tax states that have been among the hardest-fought races in recent elections. Those areas gave Democrats <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ten-takeaways-from-the-2018-midterm-elections-1541580721?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">control of the House</a> during the Trump administration and were pivotal in the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gop-gains-college-educated-and-minority-voters-in-slim-house-pickup-11668853803?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">shift to a narrow GOP majority</a> last year.</p><p> Now the issue is complicating legislation that Smith and House GOP leaders want to pass that would reverse business-tax increases that Republicans baked into the 2017 law and that took effect in recent years. Without quick action by Congress, many small research-intensive companies face enormous tax bills because of a provision that changed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/small-businesses-face-big-tax-bills-from-research-deduction-change-a189b113?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">how they deduct research costs</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1644" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ed86620f-5ff9-4126-9c33-a13c0cd2b8b6-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> While Smith&#39;s bill doesn&#39;t address the SALT cap, it would temporarily expand the standard deduction for individuals. That would make the $10,000 limit less important for some households.</p><p> Smith, who leads the House Ways and Means Committee, said he has been meeting with Republicans from high-tax states and is confident he has enough votes to get his bill through the House after Congress&#39;s summer break. It appears unlikely to become law as written. Democrats are open to business-tax changes but also want to expand the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hopes-fade-for-year-end-tax-deal-in-congress-to-aid-companies-children-11670769560?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">child tax credit</a> in ways that Republicans oppose.</p><p> Smith suggested that SALT cap changes could be possible in an end-of-year bipartisan bill—but not now.</p><p> “You don&#39;t vote against a bill because of what&#39;s not in it,” Smith said.</p><p> The SALT fight has dogged lawmakers for years. In 2017, House Republicans considered eliminating the deduction before settling on the $10,000 cap. The House passed that bill with 12 Republicans opposed, but Smith and House Speaker Kevin McCarthy (R., Calif.) don&#39;t have that cushion now with their 222-212 majority.</p><p> “I&#39;m going to continue to stand firm,” said Rep. Nick LaLota (R., NY), who represents eastern Long Island and is seeking a much higher cap, at least. “This is oxygen to many of my constituents. This is the one thing that cuts through all the partisan BS.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828397?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Rep. Nick LaLota of New York state favors raising the limit on state and local tax deductions.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Garcia, the Los Angeles-area lawmaker, would prefer no cap but said he would settle for doubling it. Leaving it at $10,000, he said, would be “a continuation of this middle-finger mentality” toward his constituents.</p><p> “I&#39;ve been very blunt with Jason Smith,” Garcia said. “We can have these conversations now when you&#39;re the chairman, or we can have these conversations in two years when you&#39;re the ranking member.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Rep. Andrew Garbarino</p> (R., NY) said lawmakers are getting cost estimates for some options to ease the cap and are looking for ways to offset the fiscal impact.<p></p><p> The 2017 law reduced taxes for most people, even in high-income, high-tax states. But the measure&#39;s changes to rates, brackets and deductions were less visible than the quick comparison of a property-tax bill with the $10,000 threshold.</p><p> Suburban districts helped give Democrats the House majority in the 2018 election—and prompted a new SALT battle. Lawmakers from California, New Jersey and New York insisted on raising or repealing the cap in any tax legislation, using a “No SALT, No Deal” rallying cry. The House eventually passed a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-spending-bill-senate-salt-immigration-11637430938?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bill with an $80,000 cap</a> , but it flopped in the Senate and never became law.</p><p> Rep. Richard Neal (D., Mass.) was Ways and Means chairman then. He watches Republicans struggle now and describes himself as overjoyed.</p><p> “In the minority, they made it sound simple,” he said. “They&#39;ve now discovered that their majority hinges upon six people who really need some SALT relief.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Should the $10,000 cap on state and local tax deductions be repealed?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The cap became more onerous over time because it doesn&#39;t increase with inflation. But states have created <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/states-help-business-owners-save-big-on-federal-taxes-with-salt-cap-workarounds-11653989400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">workarounds for business owners</a> , so the burden now largely falls on wage earners and property owners.</p><p> Neal wants the chairmanship back in 2025, which could shift the problem back onto his shoulders. If Congress does nothing, the cap disappears after that year. State and local taxes would be fully deductible, although expiring changes to the alternative minimum tax would limit the break for many.</p><p> But all of the 2017 tax cuts for individuals also expire after 2025. If lawmakers want to extend them without making deficits even larger than projected, the SALT cap is an obvious tool. The provision raises a lot of money, and it does so from people with very high incomes.</p><p> “What I would hope is that policy makers grapple with trade-offs,” said David Kamin, a former senior aide to President Biden. “If you&#39;re not going to do the SALT limitation, then there should be reduced tax cuts.”</p><p> Write to Richard Rubin at <a href="mailto:richard.rubin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">richard.rubin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/salt-deduction-cap-vexes-gop-after-vexing-democrats-after-vexing-gop-5da55434</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/salt-deduction-cap-vexes-gop-after-vexing-democrats-after-vexing-gop-5da55434<author><![CDATA[Richard Rubin]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Random Acts of Medicine’ Review: Paging Dr. Chance]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In the ER, is it better to be treated by a hot-shot heart surgeon or a rookie? It&#39;s no joke: The answer could save your life. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590112001443420266"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828676?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590112001443420266"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Alex Tabarrok</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 2, 2023 6:22 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/random-acts-of-medicine-review-paging-dr-chance-877170ec"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Most correlation isn&#39;t causation, but true wisdom comes from knowing that some correlation is causation. Take the correlation between losing weight and being given Ozempic or Wegovy in a randomized controlled trial. That correlation is causal—that&#39;s the value of a randomized controlled trial—and it explains why the new weight-loss drugs are in high demand.</p><p> Such trials are powerful but often not possible. Enter “Random Acts of Medicine: The Hidden Forces That Sway Doctors, Impact Patients, and Shape Our Health,” written by the absurdly overachieving economist and physician Anupam Jena and his only slightly less overachieving co-author, Christopher Worsham, both of them practicing physicians, researchers and professors at Harvard. Messrs. Jena and Worsham are the Freakonomicists of the medical realm—they specialize in uncovering unique “natural experiments” that shed light on medicine and medical practice.</p><p>您可能听说过左数偏差，即 7.99 美元似乎比 8 美元便宜，尽管 8 美元与 8.01 美元的差别可以忽略不计。定价中普遍存在左位数字偏差，但其影响更为普遍。例如，一辆里程表上显示里程数为 39,990 英里的汽车的售价高于一辆里程表上显示为 40,005 英里的汽车（因此，明智的做法是购买行驶里程为 40,005 英里的汽车）。左位数字偏差会出现在医学中吗？</p><p> 40 岁生日前几周因胸痛而入急诊室的人与 40 岁生日后几周因胸痛而入急诊室的人非常相似。但从图表上看，前者39岁，后者40岁。</p><p>大 40 是医生对潜在心脏病发作的启发。 Looking at more than five million patient records, the economist Stephen Coussens found that patients who were slightly over the age of 40 were almost 10% more likely to be tested for a heart attack than those just under 40. The difference shows up as a discontinuity, a jump up in the probability of being tested as patients cross their 40th birthday.</p><p>耶拿和沃舍姆先生表明，类似的不连续性也出现在整个医学领域。例如，80 岁以下的心脏病患者比 80 岁以上的心脏病患者更有可能接受冠状动脉搭桥手术。 69 岁去世的患者的肾脏更有可能接受冠状动脉搭桥手术。尽管从所有客观标准来看，这些肾脏同样具有活力和价值，但它比来自刚刚超过 70 岁的患者的肾脏更适合用于移植。也许最能说明问题的是，18 岁以下的“儿童”比 18 岁以上的“成人”更不可能服用阿片类药物，尽管这些群体在统计上无法区分。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/9687c07d-0633-4c6c-b020-bb068b8fe73a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>这些研究的目的不是对人类推理的特殊性嗤之以鼻或叹息，而是利用这些自然实验来估计医疗程序的效果。如果近 18 岁和 18 岁的青少年服用阿片类药物的方式不同的唯一原因是“儿童”和“成人”的语义，那么我们可以将处方中的不连续性用作自然实验——就好像在年龄周围开处方一样18 名被随机分配。例如，作者发现，与 18 岁以下的人相比，18 岁以上的人后来被诊断出阿片类药物相关不良事件（例如服用过量）的可能性高出 12.6%。较高的用药过量率是有价值的信息，但想象一下，试图说服机构审查委员会相信向年轻人随机开阿片类药物是合乎道德的，这是多么困难。</p><p> The authors do not always endear themselves to their colleagues. In one intriguing study spanning a decade and involving 200,000 patients, a surprising revelation emerged. Patients who happened to have a heart attack during a week when hot-shot cardiac surgeons were away at national conferences were found more likely to survive. It sounds like a joke—stay away from hospitals because that&#39;s where lots of people die—but the statistics are solid. The heart surgeons most likely to attend the national meetings also tend to be the go-getters, eager to cut and demonstrate their prowess in the operating theater. When these surgeons are away, mortality rates decrease by about 12.5%, a decrease “similar in magnitude to some of <em>the best treatments we have available for heart attacks</em> .” (Emphasis in the original). The president of the American Heart Association breezily dismissed the study&#39;s findings, saying, “there&#39;s nothing in this study that we see that would lead us to recommend a change in clinical practice.” Such dismissal in the face of significant evidence feels akin to malpractice.</p><p> There is now widespread recognition that too much medical care can be wasteful, but less recognition that it can also be harmful. Unfortunately, nearly all stakeholders, including patients, doctors, pharmaceutical firms and hospitals, are incentivized to spend and do more. Only insurance companies bear the burden of saying no. Given the inherent bias in our information sources toward positivity, it&#39;s crucial to remain vigilant about instances where medical care has exceeded reasonable boundaries.</p><p> Messrs. Jena and Worsham are serious researchers who skillfully navigate the world of medicine and natural experiments. “Random Acts of Medicine” follows the successful formula of popular-science authors like Malcolm Gladwell, Stephen Dubner and Steven Levitt, and Emily Oster, combining relatable human stories, statistical exploration and scientific explanations. But don&#39;t be fooled by the fun read; “Random Acts of Medicine” shows that the ingenious use of natural experiments can improve medicine and save lives.</p><p> <em>Mr. Tabarrok is the Bartley J. Madden Chair in Economics at George Mason University.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 02 Aug 2023 22:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/random-acts-of-medicine-review-paging-dr-chance-877170ec</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/random-acts-of-medicine-review-paging-dr-chance-877170ec<category>图书</category><category>Cardiovascular Conditions</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>cardiovascular conditions</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item></channel></rss>